post_text:
JISD Students, Staff, and Families,

JISD has spent the last couple days trying to gather as much information as possible on everyone‚Äôs situation. As of this afternoon (before all the power went out again) the City of Jasper projected that 98% of their customers would have power restored. JNEC had 6,000 customers without power in Jasper County, although much of that is south of Jasper. JISD still has many of our students and staff without power. Many folks have not yet returned or are just now returning to their homes and have lots of clean up to do. Internet is working fine in some areas and we are told will be out for several days and/or weeks in others. There are lots of people working very hard to restore power and internet and we thank them for their hard work. Because of the number of staff and students projected to be without power for several more days Jasper ISD will be closed for the rest of the week and will start back school on Tuesday, September 8th.

Please stay safe and continue to pray for those who have had devastation from this storm.

God bless,

John Seybold

post_text:
JISD Students, Staff, and Families,

We want to thank all the linemen and local officials who are working around the clock to get everyone‚Äôs power restored. While many now have electricity there are lots of areas still without. At this time, we will not have school on Monday and Tuesday and the plan is to return Wednesday; if however, there are still many without power by Monday evening, that could be extended. While we want to get students back as soon as we can, we understand the hardships many are having at this time. We will continue to communicate with our local emergency officials and make a decision with that information as soon as possible. Thank you for your patience and be safe!

God bless,

John Seybold

post_text:
JISD Students, Staff, and Families,

We are in contact with the City of Jasper, Jasper Newton Electric, and County emergency officials. Crews of lineman are working very hard to get our power restored and we sincerely thank them for all they do. At this time we are understanding it would be Monday at the earliest to restore power to most of our area and this could be pushed to later in the week. With families displaced we wanted to make a call on school as early as possible so you could plan accordingly. Because of this and the fact that once power is restored we do have some minor clean up to do around the schools, we will cancel school for Monday and Tuesday of next week at this time. We will reassess over the weekend and make other announcements as needed. Please stay safe and take care of your families at this time.

God bless,

John Seybold

post_text:
Notice From the Superintendent on School Closures for Inclement Weather:

After consulting with Jasper County Officials, at this time, Jasper ISD is cancelling school for the rest of the week beginning Tuesday, August 25- Friday, August 28. All students and staff will finish the rest of the day as normal. There is great uncertainty at this time with Hurricane/TS Laura and we are being told to be prepared for a possible category 3 hurricane. With evacuations being called or expected to be called in the counties and cities to our south (Golden Triangle) we anticipate high traffic conditions with possible contraflow on HWY 96 beginning tomorrow. Therefore, it is in the best interest of everyone that we suspend school for the week, allowing families the freedom to leave if desired. We will not be offering virtual education (Asynchronous Learning) during this time and do have extra time built into our calendar. We ask that everyone focus on your safety and health during this time and we will keep you updated with regard to school re-opening and other news.

Stay Safe,

John Seybold

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to
free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application
instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who
are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more
information, visit http://hhs.texas.gov/pebt or call 833-613-6220.

Did you know that neglecting your reading for one month will cause you to lose an average of two months of academic progress? Don‚Äôt let this happen to you. Be a part of the Jasper Reads Initiative. Read any book of your choice and log your books into the online form located on the Jasper ISD website or any campus websites. Simply find the "Jasper READS" icon and click to log your books!

Elementary students will get Accelerated Reader points, which can be used to earn rewards such as pizza, parties, and field trips. Secondary students will also be given rewards, but are not a part of the Accelerated Reader Program.

By continuing your reading at home, you will ensure that you are ready for school when we resume. Not only will you strengthen your mind, but you will also earn rewards. Earning rewards while reading what you enjoy has never been so easy, so get busy and start logging those books!

post_text: Jasper ISD has received word that their shipments of prepackaged meals for the week of April 20th has been cancelled from their supplier. JISD Child nutrition has tried all other USDA School lunch program approved vendors but none can deliver the 5 day meal kits at this time, that meet the USDA requirements, due to the high demand in our country. JISD will continue to contact vendors and as soon as shipments are available plans are to continue the once a week meal delivery system. Please know we want to provide this service and know how much some of our students depend on these meals. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we try to continue to serve our students and community in the safest way possible.

post_text:
CHANGES TO JASPER ISD'S MEAL SERVICE

Due to numerous issues with being able to receive our shipments of food and continued concerns for safety; beginning Monday, April 6th Jasper ISD's meal service will reduced to once a week. Meal kits will contain 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches. Meals may be picked up at our curbside service locations at Few Primary and Jasper Junior High on Mondays from 11 to 12. On Monday only, we will deliver 5 day meal kits via regular bus routes.

Also due to regulations there will not be any meal distribution the week of April 13th because it is Jasper ISD's scheduled Spring Break. Jasper ISD knows how important these meals are to our students we will continue to provide the food in the safest way possible. Thank you all for your patience and understanding. We are very grateful to our Child Nutrition and Transportation employees who have Worked so diligently to maintain our meal program services to your families.

Good Morning,

Jasper ISD Child Nutrition Staff and Bus Drivers are working hard to deliver no cost meals to Children 18 and under.
You do not have to sign up just be out at a regular bus stop between 10:30 and 12. If you do not ride the bus, please call 384-2252 to give us your information.

We also have grab and go meals available for pick up at Jasper Junior High and Few Primary. Currently, breakfast is 8:00 to 8:30 and lunch is 11:00 to 12:00; however, beginning Monday we will serve lunch and breakfast, (for the next day), between 11:00 and 12:00.

All meals delivered or picked up Thursday will include meals for Friday each week. There are no open campuses or meal deliveries on Fridays.

Thank you for your patience and grace as we are getting better and delivering more and more meals each day.

post_text:
Achieve 3000 is excited to announce the Make the Break holiday contest, their way of supporting outstanding student achievement even while students are out of school.

Here's how it works:

Students who complete at least five lessons in KidBiz3000, TeenBiz3000, or Empower3000 between December 21, 2019, and January 5, 2019, will be entered in state-wide drawings for a chance to win Sony Headphones. Students who complete 10 lessons will be entered twice! With over 50 winners, students have a good chance of getting a prize!

post_text: We are proud to announce Jasper Kicker Alex Mijares (Class of 2020) has been invited to the 2019 Kicking World National Showcase taking place this coming weekend on December 7-8 in Austin, Texas. He earned the invitation earlier this season by having a ‚Äòwow‚Äô performance in the pressure competitions, competing against some of the best kickers from over 25 states. post_text:
The Texas Education Agency is committed to making sure you are informed and have an accurate picture of your child‚Äôs progress. On June 12th, parents can access their child‚Äôs STAAR results and a suite of other resources to support summer learning at home.

The Student Portal will be updated by June 12, 2019. Parents can access their child‚Äôs results using a unique access code or look up their code with their birthdate on https://www.texasassessment.com/. Parents can also view the assessment questions, their child‚Äôs answers to the questions, and correct answers and rationales. Additionally, parents can view their child‚Äôs performance relative to the campus, district, and state.

https://www.texasassessment.com/families/understanding-the-test-score/

Campuses will receive paper copies of the STAAR Report Card (SRC) to distribute to parents over the summer. The unique access code can be provided to you from your child‚Äôs campus, accessed through the portal through look up, or it is located on the STAAR Report Card.

post_text: Jasper ISD would like to thank The Jasper Economic Development Corporation (JEDCO) along with the Jasper Football Booster Club for making it possible for the purchase of a New Video Board to enhance the Jasper Athletic Complex. The new stadium will have a new video board that can be used for multiple events, which include football, soccer, track, graduation, etc.. The Jasper Economic Develop Corporation presented the board with a check for $62,000.00 which will be added to $10,000.00 from the Football Booster Club, and $12,000.00 from the Athletic Department for the project. We are excited about the new addition to our stadium.

post_text: At about 12:50 pm on 3/21/2018 Jasper Jr. High was contacted regarding a report of shots fired on 2nd St that was heard over a police scanner. Jasper Jr. High and Parnell were immediately put on lockdown and our Emergency Action Plan was put in place. JPD was contacted and it was confirmed by 2 sources that the shots were reported to be fired on 2nd St. in Kirbyville. Once confirmation was received and campuses were checked for extra precaution the lock down was lifted. Thanks to the staff of both schools, our School Resource officers and the Jasper Police Department for their quick action and for keeping our students and staff safe. Although this turned out to be a false alarm JISD felt to keep our students and staff safe it was necessary to lock down both campuses.

post_text: Other schools districts in our region have experienced threats or rumors, but JISD wants to be proactive and have plans in place. The extra patrols are just precautionary at this time.
text: Other schools districts in our region have experienced threats or rumors, but JISD wants to be proactive and have plans in place. The extra patrols are just precautionary at this time.

post_text:
In the aftermath of the Florida tragedy, sadly many schools in our region and around the country are receiving rumors of copycat events or threats made through social media. We are taking all precautions and will thoroughly investigate every report we receive. Local law enforcement has been involved throughout the process and continues to work directly with the district. We are taking extra precaution and have increased law enforcement presence to ensure student safety. The safety of our students and staff is always our first priority, and all threats will be investigated thoroughly by administration, and law enforcement. Please speak to your child about the serious repercussions of making, or even sharing anything threatening on social media.

If you do have concerns or hear of any threats, please do not hesitate to call your child's campus administration, John Seybold at 409-382-1065, or Dr. Gerald Hudson at 409-382-1068. At that time we will investigate fully and involve the proper authorities.

post_text:
Just an update......As a precautionary measure Jasper ISD continues to disinfect classrooms and buildings during evenings and on weekends. This Flu season we have had extra reminders in place to wash hands and be conscious of spreading germs.

Tips to stop the spreading of germs and viruses:

Try to avoid close contact with sick people.
While sick, limit contact with others as much as possible to keep from infecting them.
If you are sick with flu symptoms, it is recommended that you stay home for at least 24 hours after your fever is gone except to get medical care or for other necessities. (Your fever should be gone for 24 hours without the use of a fever-reducing medicine.)
Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze. Throw the tissue in the trash after you use it.
Wash your hands often with soap and water. If soap and water are not available, use provided sanitizers.
Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth. Germs spread this way.
Thank you in all you do to help us keep our students and staff safe and well!

Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze. Throw the tissue in the trash after you use it.
Wash your hands often with soap and water. If soap and water are not available, use provided sanitizers.

Tips to stop the spreading of germs and viruses:

Try to avoid close contact with sick people.

While sick, limit contact with others as much as possible to keep from infecting them.

If you are sick with flu symptoms, it is recommended that you stay home for at least 24 hours after your fever is gone except to get medical care or for other necessities. (Your fever should be gone for 24 hours without the use of a fever-reducing medicine.)

Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze. Throw the tissue in the trash after you use it.

Wash your hands often with soap and water. If soap and water are not available, use provided sanitizers.

Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth. Germs spread this way.

Thank you in all you do to help us keep our students and staff safe and well!

First and foremost, I want to publicly thank the custodians, maintenance workers, and various employees of Jasper ISD for getting our campuses ready for school on Tuesday, September 5th. Although this is a difficult time for our families, neighbors, community, and staff, the goal is to get our district back to normalcy as soon as possible.

Both breakfast and lunch will be provided to ALL students at no charge until September 30th, 2017.

We will continue to monitor our operations and provide support for our students and staff, who are having difficulties with the recent events. As always, we appreciate your support.

Gerald Hudson, Ed.D.

The Jasper ISD Board of Trustees voted and signed a resolution to pursue the opportunity of developing an innovative plan for a District of Innovation on Monday, April 10, 2017. The District of Innovation concept, passed by the 84th Legislative Session in House Bill 1842, gives traditional independent school districts most of the flexibilities available to Texas‚Äô open-enrollment charter schools. There are several potential benefits of becoming a District of Innovation. To seek feedback surrounding the needs of the students in Jasper ISD a survey has been placed on our website. This is another way to continue to provide a quality learning environment for every child. The survey also includes two links to more information about an innovative district.

Thank you,

Stacey Woolems, Executive Director
Jasper Independent School District
Curriculum / Instruction and Special Services

Friday, April 21st - 2017 Project Graduation Fundraiser
Jasper Ford Lincoln and Lincoln Motor Company will host a Driven to Give Event from 9:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. on Friday, April 21st.

The Driven to Give Event was developed as a fun, engaging way to help high schools raise money to support their sports and extracurricular activities.
Lincoln Dealerships partner with local high schools to conduct test-drive fund raising events. For every valid test-drive completed, Lincoln Motor Company will donate $20 to the participating high school, up to $6,000!

Lincoln Motor Company will donate $20 for each test-drive to 2017 Project Graduation. There is a goal of 300 test drives or $6,000. Test -drives are limited to one per household. You must be 18 years old and have a valid driver's license in order to test-drive.

Come out and support the Class of 2017 Project Graduation!

Jasper Junior High School
March 29, 2017 at 4:36 PM ¬∑

Jasper ISD was notified that we were under a tornado warning about 4:00 on 3-29. Students that remained on campus at that time were moved to secure areas to seek shelter. Buses were instructed to seek the safest nearby area and some that were close enough returned to transportation. At this time all students still on buses and on campus are safe and will remain until it is safe to resume afternoon routes. Thank you for your patience and helping to keep our kids safe.
